<section class="section" id="litellm">
  <h2><span class="num">02 — The LiteLLM Door</span>How a Forty-Minute Window Reached the Switchboard</h2>
  <p>The breach entered through a piece of open-source software that had nothing to do with Mercor's core product. LiteLLM is a Python library used by developers to route requests between applications and large language models. It is downloaded millions of times per month. In late March 2026, according to cybersecurity-trade reporting, a threat group calling itself TeamPCP used compromised maintainer credentials to upload two malicious versions of the LiteLLM package — versions 1.82.7 and 1.82.8 — to PyPI, the standard Python package index.</p>

  <div class="mercor-install-wrap">
    <div class="mercor-install-header">~/mercor-pipeline$</div>
    <div class="mercor-install-body">
      <div class="mercor-install-cmd">$ pip install litellm</div>
      <div class="mercor-install-output">Collecting litellm</div>
      <div class="mercor-install-output">&nbsp;&nbsp;Downloading litellm-1.82.7-py3-none-any.whl (4.2 MB)</div>
      <div class="mercor-install-output">Installing collected packages: litellm</div>
      <div class="mercor-install-success">Successfully installed litellm-1.82.7</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mercor-install-note">According to cybersecurity-trade reporting, the trojanized package remained on PyPI for roughly 40 minutes before being pulled. Anyone who installed it during that window pulled the attacker's code along with it.</div>
  </div>

  <p>The trojanized packages, according to Cybersecurity News and The Next Web, contained base64-encoded malware that executed on import, harvesting environment variables, API keys, cloud credentials, and database secrets, and exfiltrating them to a server controlled by the attackers. No primary malware-analysis report from a major security firm has been published in the public record. The technical details come from cybersecurity trade outlets citing researchers at Wiz and statements from Mandiant Consulting CTO Charles Carmakal, who told reporters more than a thousand SaaS environments had been affected by TeamPCP's supply-chain attacks.</p>
  <p>Mercor was one of those environments. On March 31, 2026, the company publicly confirmed it had been hit. Spokesperson Heidi Hagberg told TechCrunch the company had "moved promptly to contain and remediate the incident" and was "conducting a thorough investigation supported by leading third-party forensics experts." Hagberg described Mercor as "one of thousands of companies" affected by the LiteLLM compromise. She declined to answer follow-up questions about whether the incident was connected to Lapsus$ claims and whether any data had been exfiltrated.</p>
  <p>The claims came from a group calling itself Lapsus$. On its dark-web leak site, Lapsus$ posted that it had taken approximately four terabytes of data from Mercor — including, by Lapsus$'s own description, 939 GB of source code, a 211 GB user database, internal Slack communications, Tailscale VPN configurations, and roughly three terabytes of stored video and document files. None of these volumes have been independently confirmed. Multiple outlets reported the claim, but all trace to the same Lapsus$ posting. The relationship between TeamPCP and Lapsus$ remains contested: Wiz security researchers described a collaborative arrangement to Cybersecurity News; TechCrunch reported the relationship "remains unclear."</p>
  <p>Mercor's only additional on-record statement, issued to the Wall Street Journal on April 23, was: "We strongly dispute the speculative claims in these lawsuits and look forward to presenting the facts at the appropriate time and place."</p>
</section>

<div class="phantom-wrap">
