</div>
<p class="canvas-note"><strong>The Layer</strong> — Tiny particles rise from a dense bottom field into a violet chain of connected nodes spanning the middle; a fracture splits one node and a sharp pulse erupts upward into a large lab node at the top, which shudders red; the chain repairs; the particles keep rising.</p>

<section class="section" id="suits">
  <h2><span class="num">03 — The Suits</span>Seven Filings, One Tape</h2>
  <p>The lawsuits began the day after Mercor's disclosure.</p>
  <p>On April 1, 2026, Lisa Gill of Wahiawa, Hawaii, filed what became the lead class action: Gill v. Mercor.io Corporation, case number 3:26-cv-02831-JCS, in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California, represented by Edelsberg Law. The same day, two additional suits — Deboni v. Mercor (3:26-cv-02821) and Esson v. Mercor (3:26-cv-02839) — were filed in the same court. On April 5, White and Beltran v. Mercor was filed in the Northern District of Texas (6:26-CV-00143-H), the only suit to name additional co-defendants beyond Mercor itself. Bloomberg Law reported a separate filing under the Illinois Artificial Intelligence Video Interview Act — one of the first federal cases under that 2020 statute. By April 23, the Wall Street Journal counted at least seven class-action lawsuits.</p>
  <p>The data categories the complaints allege were exposed span the full depth of what Mercor collected from its contractors: full names, Social Security numbers, recorded video interviews, facial-biometric data extracted from those interviews, identity documents including passports, background checks, W-9 tax forms, computer screenshots captured by employee-monitoring software that the White/Beltran complaint identifies as Insightful, and internal Slack communications. The lead complaint estimates more than 40,000 current and former contractors and customers were affected. Mercor has not confirmed that number.</p>
  <p>The plaintiffs' theory of harm goes beyond exposure. The complaints allege Mercor used recorded interviews to train AI models for clients, monitored contractors' computers continuously, and trained client models on materials potentially owned by other companies. Mercor disputes these claims. They are pre-discovery allegations. They may not survive contact with the documentary record. But the question they force into discovery is novel: what is the legal status of a recording made for one purpose and used to train a model that generates similar recordings? No appellate court has answered this. The Illinois AIVFA suit — only the second federal filing under that statute, according to Bloomberg Law — will be among the first attempts.</p>
  <p>The Gill complaint alleges Mercor failed to implement multi-factor authentication, encryption of sensitive data during storage and transmission, access controls limiting employee data access, and system monitoring for suspicious activity. These are standard boilerplate in data-breach litigation. What is not standard is the surveillance infrastructure the complaints describe: the White/Beltran complaint alleges contractors were required to use monitoring software that randomly captured screenshots during work sessions, creating a secondary data archive that neither the contractors nor, apparently, the security apparatus was designed to protect.</p>

