<section class="section" id="lateral">
  <h2><span class="num">04 — The Lateral Move</span>From Privacy Story to Security Story</h2>
  <p>For the first week after March 31, the Mercor breach was treated as a contractor-privacy story — a large but familiar pattern. A company collected too much data, protected it too poorly, and lost it. The coverage focused on Social Security numbers and passports.</p>
  <p>Then came the Mythos reporting. Bloomberg published its account on April 21. Tom's Hardware confirmed the mechanism independently: the attackers had combined Anthropic's internal file-system naming conventions — present in material taken from Mercor — with a compromised contractor credential to locate Mythos within Anthropic's infrastructure. No independent technical reconstruction of the access path has been published.</p>
  <p>What the reporting revealed reframed the entire breach. The contractor data was not just personal information. It was operational knowledge of how the labs organize their own work — naming conventions, file-system structures, credential patterns. A breach in the middle layer gave outsiders a map of the top layer.</p>
  <p>The labs responded at different speeds. Meta paused all work with Mercor, characterized as indefinite, confirmed first by WIRED citing two sources and subsequently by a Meta spokesperson to the Wall Street Journal. OpenAI told reporters the breach "in no way affects OpenAI user data" and said it was investigating whether proprietary datasets were exposed, but had not paused or ended its contracts with Mercor. Google said it was assessing the breach's scope. Anthropic offered no public comment on the Mercor relationship beyond confirming the Mythos unauthorized access.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="signal">
  <h2><span class="num">05 — Signal</span>What This Layer Looks Like Now</h2>
  <p>Meta's pause is one client. Mercor reported more than $1 billion in annualized revenue before the breach, according to The Information. Whether that survives the lawsuits and Meta's freeze is unknown. The company's last confirmed valuation was $10 billion, as of the October 2025 Series C. No post-breach secondary-market valuation has been publicly reported.</p>
  <p>Mercor is not the only company in this layer. Scale AI, Surge AI, Invisible Technologies, and others operate similar contractor pools, managing the human labor that turns raw model outputs into refined model behavior. None has disclosed a comparable breach. None publishes meaningful information about what employee-monitoring, biometric-capture, or training-use practices its contracts authorize. The layer is opaque by design.</p>
  <p>The Mythos chain raises a question that the lawsuits cannot answer: when a frontier lab's internal naming conventions and a single contractor credential are enough to access an unannounced model, the perimeter of "the lab" includes every contractor's laptop on every continent. There is no current framework — regulatory, contractual, or technical — that treats it that way. The labs treat their vendors as outside the perimeter. The attackers treated them as inside it.</p>
  <p>No independent technical reconstruction of the LiteLLM compromise, the Mercor exfiltration scope, or the Mythos access path has been published in the public record. The claims rest on Mercor's brief disclosure, Lapsus$'s self-reporting, the lawsuits' allegations, and the reporting from Bloomberg and Tom's Hardware on the Mythos linkage. What is confirmed is narrower than what is alleged — and what is alleged is narrower than what may have happened.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="tape">
  <h2><span class="num">06 — The Tape</span>What the Contractors Now Know</h2>
  <p>The contractors who taught the model now know something the model does not. They know what their faces looked like on the tape. They know what their screens showed during the recording. They know that when they signed up to label data, the data was them.</p>
  <p>They know it because a collection of court filings told them — months after the file was already taken, weeks after the file already opened a door at a lab they had never heard of, in a city they may have never visited, working on a model whose name they will never learn.</p>
  <p>The lawsuits will determine what Mercor did wrong. The lawsuits cannot determine who else, in this layer, is doing the same thing right now.</p>
</section>

